  "summary": "# Weekly Market Briefing \u2014 May 24, 2026\n\n## 1. Market Overview\nBroad indices closed higher across the board, with risk-on positioning evident. SPY gained +0.95% to $745.64 and QQQ outperformed at +1.65% ($717.54), while small caps led decisively \u2014 IWM surged +3.32%, signaling broadening participation beyond mega-caps. DIA (+1.83%) and VTI (+1.22%) confirm the constructive tone. The simultaneous rally in equities and bonds (TLT +1.34%) suggests softening yield expectations, though weakness in gold (-1.10%) and crypto (BTC -1.47%) muddies the macro picture.\n\n## 2. Sector Performance\n**Outperformers:**\n- **XLK (+3.46%)** \u2014 Tech led, driven by semiconductor strength\n- **XLU (+3.21%)** \u2014 Utilities rally aligns with falling-rate narrative\n- **XLV (+2.86%)** \u2014 Healthcare boosted by pharma names\n- **XLY (+2.46%)** \u2014 Consumer Discretionary firm on small-cap tailwinds\n\n**Underperformers:**\n- **XLE (-1.80%)** \u2014 Energy weak amid oil softness (XOM -3.47%, CVX -1.50%)\n- **XLC (-1.30%)** \u2014 Communications dragged by GOOGL (-3.52%)\n- **XLP (-1.28%)** \u2014 Defensive staples lagged risk-on rotation\n\nThe pattern \u2014 Tech + Utilities up, Energy + Staples down \u2014 suggests a duration-friendly, rate-sensitive trade.\n\n## 3. Notable Movers\n- **AMD +11.05%** ($467.51) on heavy volume (33M) \u2014 the week's standout, likely on AI/data center catalysts\n- **MRK +8.75%** ($122.41) \u2014 major pharma breakout\n- **AAPL +3.69%** ($308.82) \u2014 solid tech leadership on 40M volume\n- **TSLA +3.91%** ($426.01)\n- **NVDA -3.14%** on massive 168M volume \u2014 notable divergence from AMD; possible rotation within semis\n- **GOOGL -3.52%** \u2014 weakest mega-cap\n- **VZ & T both +3.40%** \u2014 telecom strength alongside utilities\n- **XOM -3.47%** \u2014 energy capitulation\n\n## 4. Key Metrics\n- **Valuation stretch:** TSLA P/E 383.8, AMD 156.4, PLTR 153.8, ABBV 105.2, SHOP 101 \u2014 premium multiples remain elevated\n- **SPY P/E at 28.0** sits above historical averages; QQQ at 35.0 reflects continued tech premium\n- **IWM P/E 19.6** \u2014 small caps still relatively cheap, supporting the rotation thesis\n- **Bond yields easing:** TLT +1.34% implies long rates declining, consistent with utility/REIT strength (XLRE +1.85%, VNQ +1.85%)\n- **Crypto weakness across the board** (-1% to -2.65%) decouples from equity risk appetite \u2014 worth monitoring\n- **Volume note:** NVDA's 168M shares on a down week suggests distribution\n\n## 5. Themes to Watch\n1. **Small-cap rotation** \u2014 IWM's +3.32% vs. SPY's +0.95% is the largest divergence in weeks; sustainability depends on rate trajectory\n2. **Semi divergence** \u2014 AMD vs. NVDA performance gap (+11% vs -3%) warrants scrutiny on AI capex narrative\n3. **Energy breakdown** \u2014 XLE's decline alongside both majors falling could signal demand concerns or supply shifts\n4. **Rate-sensitive bid** \u2014 Utilities, REITs, and Treasuries rallying together suggest market is pricing in easier policy\n5. **Crypto/equity decoupling** \u2014 Risk-on in stocks but risk-off in digital assets is unusual\n6. **Pharma momentum** \u2014 MRK and ABBV strength; watch for sector-wide follow-through\n7. **GOOGL weakness** \u2014 Underperformance vs. peers worth tracking for company-specific catalysts\n\n*Next week: monitor Fed commentary, PCE data, and whether small-cap leadership persists.*",
